{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"7f53ef3a-598a-48a5-afdd-2c3344028070","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's the rundown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. Azure DevOps matches test history by ID, so every test looks \"new.\" You can restore the old IDs by adding this to your project file:\n\n```xml\n<TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n```\n\nOr, if you're using a `.runsettings` file:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>DisplayName</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer tied to any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` (or `TestResultsDirectory`, etc.) throws because no test is running yet. This is your file's problem on **line 13**:\n\n```csharp\nvar testName = context.TestName; // throws in v4\n```\n\n**Fix:** Remove or guard that access. If you need per-test setup, use `[TestInitialize]` instead, where `TestContext` is properly bound to a test.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Other key v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|---|---|\n| **`[DataRow]` type coercion** | v4 is stricter — implicit conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) that worked in v3 may now fail at compile time or runtime. |\n| **`Assert.AreEqual` for collections** | v4 compares collections structurally by default in some overloads; tests relying on reference equality may flip. |\n| **`[AssemblyInitialize]`/`[AssemblyCleanup]`** | Same `TestContext` scoping change as `[ClassInitialize]` — no test-level properties available. |\n| **Parallel execution defaults** | v4 enables method-level parallelism by default. Tests with shared mutable state may start failing intermittently. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable it if needed. |\n| **`DeploymentItem`** | Behavior changed; paths resolve differently. Verify any file-deployment tests. |\n\n---\n\n### Recommended fix for your code\n\n```csharp\n// Remove TestName access from ClassInitialize — it's class-scoped in v4\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // General class-level setup only (no test-specific properties)\n}\n\n// Use TestInitialize for per-test work\n[TestInitialize]\npublic void TestInit()\n{\n    var testName = TestContext.TestName; // safe here\n}\n```\n\nWould you like me to apply this fix to `SetupTests.cs`?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fb464fce-1470-46d0-8439-27e7a0c005e5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on known MSTest v4 changes. Let me address each issue:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps** — MSTest v4 changed the default **test ID generation strategy**. In v3, the fully qualified test name was used. In v4, a new stable ID strategy was introduced that changes how test IDs are computed, which means Azure DevOps sees them as completely new tests (no history match).\n\n2. **`TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`** — In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test method. \n\nSince `[ClassInitialize]` runs at the class level rather than for individual tests, accessing `TestName` will throw an exception because there's no single test name in that context—this is an intentional design change. There are several other breaking changes worth being aware of in MSTest v4 that I should walk through.","outputTokens":961,"requestId":"4C23:3C6161:10EBFF4:147FACA:6A01473B"},"id":"b561fa58-d1fc-4d30-8403-c4c7b1adb48c","timestamp":"2026-05-11T03:04:48.298Z","parentId":"edf845bd-4132-4ffc-a327-eb4e57b291e8"}
